[1] Saudi Arabia, 4 new cases, 5 deaths - MOH
Date: 13 May 2014
Source: Saudi MOH 13 May 2014 [edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/en/CoronaNew/PressReleases/Pages/mediastatement-2014-05-13-001.aspx


MOH: 4 New Confirmed Corona Cases Recorded - 13 May 2014
----------------------------
Daily Report on the Coronavirus (MERS-CoV)
As of 12 pm Local Time in Makkah on Tuesday, [13 May 2014]

The total number of confirmed cases over the past 24 hours: 4 cases
Recovered and discharged cases that previously tested positive and are now negative: 6 cases
The total number of deaths: 5 cases (1 case was recorded over the past 24 hours, and the other 4 are from previously confirmed cases.)

Overview of the Health Status of the Cases:
- 3 stable cases
- 1 death

Health situation of the cases in detail:
A. Riyadh:
- A 34-year-old woman developed respiratory symptoms on [11 May 2014] and is in home isolation. Her condition is stable. She has been in contact with a confirmed case.
- A 50-year-old woman developed respiratory symptoms on [11 May 2014]. Her condition is stable and she in home isolation. She has been in contact with a confirmed case.
- A 20-year-old woman was admitted to a government hospital on [9 May 2014] with heart problems. She developed respiratory symptoms on [11 May 2014]. Her condition is stable.
- A 69-year-old man suffering from diabetes and chronic heart disease was admitted to a government hospital on [28 Apr 2014] due to heart disease. He developed respiratory symptoms on [11 May 2014]. A day later, he was admitted to the ICU. He passed away on [12 May 2014].

Deaths from previously reported cases:
- A 54-year-old man passed away on [12 May 2014]. He was previously recorded as a confirmed case in Jeddah.
- A 60-year-old man passed away on [12 May 2014]. He was previously recorded as a confirmed case in Jeddah.
- A 53-year-old woman passed away on [12 May 2014]. She was previously recorded as a confirmed case in Jeddah.
- A 29-year-old man passed away on [12 May 2014]. He was previously recorded as a confirmed case in Jeddah.

Recovered and discharged cases that previously tested positive and are now negative:
- A 48-year-old man was discharged from a government hospital in Jeddah.
- A 55-year-old man was discharged from a government hospital in Jeddah.
- A 47-year-old woman was discharged from a government hospital in Riyadh.
- A 51-year-old woman was discharged from a government hospital in Riyadh.
- A 31-year-old woman was discharged from a government hospital in Riyadh.
- A 55-year-old woman tested negative for MERS coronavirus. She is being treated at a government hospital in Riyadh for other health reasons.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the Saudi MOH website, with the addition of these 4 newly confirmed cases and 5 deaths reported, there have been a total of 495 laboratory confirmed infections of MERS-CoV including 152 deaths in Saudi Arabia since June 2012 (in prior comments, this moderator has used September 2012 as the start of "reporting" of cases; the actual time of onset of the 1st reported case in Saudi Arabia was in June 2012).

In the above descriptions of newly confirmed cases, 2 were reported as known contacts of confirmed cases and were on home isolation in stable condition, and the other 2 were apparently admitted to a hospital for other health reasons prior to the onset of symptoms consistent with MERS-CoV infection (although in one instance, there was a 24-hour period between hospitalization for heart disease and onset of symptoms consistent with MERS-CoV infection). One wonders whether these individuals had been previously identified as contacts of cases and initial laboratory results were negative for MERS-CoV infection. There are so many unknowns -- the natural history of MERS-CoV infection -- what is the true transmission rate amongst close family/household contacts? What is the true symptomatic to asymptomatic infection ratio? What proportion of individuals originally identified as "stable" progress to serious disease requiring ICU (intensive care unit) treatment? How is transmission occurring in hospitals? Is it pure person to person? Fomites?

If this moderator's calculations are correct, with the addition of the cases today (13 May 2014: 4 cases, 5 deaths), globally, there have now been 585 laboratory confirmed MERS-CoV infected individuals including 179 deaths.

A map showing the locations of newly confirmed MERS-CoV infections and deaths can be found at the source URL. - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] USA (Florida) ex Saudi Arabia
Date: 13 May 2014
Source: NBC news [edited]
http://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/florida-hospital-workers-who-treated-mers-patient-also-ill-n104276


Two of the health care workers who treated a MERS patient in Florida have come down with respiratory symptoms and are being tested to see whether they may have caught the mysterious virus from him, hospital officials say.

In at least one of the cases, it is almost certain not to be MERS; the staffer started showing symptoms just a day after treating the patient, who is the 2nd person to be diagnosed with MERS in the United States.

The incubation period for MERS -- meaning the time it takes from being in contact with someone who is infected to showing the 1st symptoms -- is usually about 5 days.

"We want to be extra cautious," said Dr. Antonio Crespo, infectious disease specialist and chief quality officer for the P. Phillips Hospital in Orlando. "These 2 people were in contact with the patient without a mask."

One of the staffers was treated and sent home, and the other is in a special isolation room at the hospital, like the MERS patient is.

Health care workers who treat patients with the virus are the most likely to become infected themselves, probably because of the close contact.

Crespo said 20 health care workers at 2 hospitals who may have been exposed to the virus are keeping themselves isolated at home and being regularly tested for MERS.

The MERS patient, a 44-year-old health care worker from Saudi Arabia, was visiting family in Orlando when he became ill enough to visit the emergency room on [8 May 2014]. He's been in the hospital since [9 May 2014] and has been kept isolated under special conditions ever since doctors suspected he might have MERS.

Middle East respiratory syndrome virus (MERS) is on the rise, especially in Saudi Arabia. It's infected more than 500 people since it was 1st identified in 2012, spread to 16 countries, and killed about a quarter of its victims.

The 1st U.S. patient with MERS, also a health care worker who had been working in Saudi Arabia, has gone home after treatment in an Indiana hospital.

Doctors say the risk to the general public is very low. MERS is not terribly infectious. Studies of those who have become infected show they were usually in close and prolonged contact with a victim. But it's a new virus, and very deadly compared to something like the flu, so doctors want to err on the side of caution.

Health detectives are tracking down everyone who flew on 4 flights with the MERS patient, from Saudi Arabia to London, then to Boston, Atlanta, and Orlando.

The trouble with treating any respiratory virus is they all have similar symptoms: fever, cough, body aches. And people get these viruses all the time. It takes about 2 days to test for something specific like MERS. If MERS is suspected, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention advises hospitals to just act as if it were MERS. So patients are being kept in special isolation rooms with strict hygiene procedures. "When we go and visit the patient -- I went this morning -- I have to wear a special mask called an N-95 (respirator). I have to wear a gown and gloves. Once we get out of the room we dispose of everything," Crespo told reporters.

The MERS patient also visited a 2nd hospital, the Orlando Regional Medical Center. Officials at the P. Phillips Hospital are not precisely sure why -- he didn't go to seek treatment, they say -- but to be extra sure, they've asked 5 hospital staff who were in contact with him to stay home for 14 days, get tested for MERS, and stay away from other people.

But because he did not feel well, the patient didn't travel around the region and mostly stayed home, doctors said. He did not go visit any tourist attractions in Orlando.

Dr. Ken Michaels of the Florida Department of Health in Orange County says hospitals should prepare for cases like this. "I don't think we have seen the last of this," he told reporters. "We are going to see more travel from this part of the world."

With a surge of cases in Saudi Arabia, people are sure to carry the virus on trips with them, Michaels said, something that CDC and World Health Organization officials have also said.

Both of the men who carried MERS to the U.S. worked in hospitals where MERS patients were treated, one in Jeddah, one in Riyadh.

There's no specific treatment for MERS. Patients get what's called supportive care, intravenous fluids, oxygen or a breathing tube if needed, and pain medications.

[Byline: Maggie Fox]

--
