[3] MERS and PHEIC - opinion piece from the Region
Date: 13 May 2014
From: Jawad Mofleh <jmofleh@yahoo.com> [edited]


MERS virus is member of the coronavirus family that not only affects humans but can affect some animals as well. The virus can have a wide range of clinical presentations, from asymptomatic cases, to mild flu, to illness as severe as SARS.

Coronaviruses are infamous for the SARS global epidemic in 2003. MERS, a novel member of this family, was 1st detected in September 2012 in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, though later on, it was proven that even before this date, the virus had victims in Jordan, a country neighboring Saudi Arabia.

The World Health Organization has reported 496 cases and around 112 deaths up to 7 May 2014. Countries reporting these cases are Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait, Lebanon, Egypt, UAE, Yemen, USA, UK, Germany, France, Malaysia and Greece. All cases outside the Arabian Peninsula are related to Arabian cases in one way or another. In July 2013, the World Health Organization announced that the virus is not a public health emergency of international concern [PHEIC] but a serious and great concern.

As reported earlier, countries reported 496 cases till 7 May 2014; the number of cases detected between September 2012 to the end of December 2013 were 176 cases and 74 deaths; during the months of January and February 2014, the number of cases remained low, and only around 26 cases were detected.

We are witnessing a large spike in the disease during April and May 2014, with 290 new cases and 26 deaths. The majority of the cases are being reported from Saudi Arabia with some cases from UAE (Abu Dhabi), Jordan, Lebanon, Egypt, Yemen and USA. As per a BMJ news item quoting Dr. Ala Alwan, Regional Director of WHO EMR, 3/4ths of the recently reported cases are secondary cases that contracted the disease in a hospital, and only one quarter are primary cases. Health care workers are among infected cases.

Detection of large numbers of cases of MERS in a short time and confined to a small area is a source of concern for this region and also for the world. The EMR region is hosting polio, the disease for which WHO announced a PHEIC on 5 May 2014, and now MERS has become a growing concern for the region.

Though it is still not clear why this sudden increase in the number of MERS cases happened, one can think of the following possible explanations:

1 - The virus has undergone a genetic shift or drift, which enables the virus to transmit from animal to human or human to human more easily than before.

2 - Community transmission is much wider than expected, and once we find a severe case and investigate it, we can detect many other cases attached to it. Hence, probably, we are detecting the tip of the iceberg in some of the settings.

It is impossible to prevent the emergence new pathogens, but on-time detection of novel infections as well as the extension of their spread among humans and animals can prevent further spread, reduce loss of lives, and economical losses.

In the last 2 years, the case definition which has been used for surveillance and case detection paid attention to severe cases (SARS infections) and missed asymptomatic and mild cases and caused further spread of infection. Also, a huge gap and delay in recognition and detection of animal reservoirs caused more spread and infection of more people.

Though we do not understand the exact basic reproductive rate/ratio (R0) of the virus, if we assume that the R0 of MERS is 1-2, we simply missed at least 500-1000 infections in a very optimistic scenario, unless we are sure that all possible contacts of primary cases and contacts of contacts have been investigated. This means that, basically, we are claiming that all individuals involved in one way or another in the chain of infection/transmission have been thoroughly investigated, and no one has bee left behind.

The other question is why only secondary cases have been reported from Saudi Arabia and richer countries in the region (except one case in Yemen) or developed countries? Keeping in mind that probably thousands of individuals are working in cities like Jeddah, Riyadh and UAE and there are regular direct flights from these cities to poorer countries of the region, I believe that health systems in those countries are unable to detect MERS cases because they do not have the capacities to diagnose the virus, and also their surveillance systems do not have the specificity to pick up on the novel viruses. If correct, this delay in detection and diagnosis enhances transmission and spread of the virus, and hence causes a bigger threat for health security. Thus, another PHIEC is coming soon.

[Note: The piece contains views of the author and do not reflect institutional ideas and stands.]

--
Dr. Jawad Mofleh
Associate Director for Science
Eastern Mediterranean
Public Health Network
<jmofleh@yahoo.com>

[The IHR Emergency Committee met today (13 May 2014) and will be meeting tomorrow, addressing the issue of whether the ongoing MERS-CoV activity in the Arabian Peninsula is a Public Health Event of International Concern (PHEIC). Results of this committee review should be available shortly after the committee meetings and discussions have finished. Major concerns at the international level surround the potential importation of cases to resource poor countries with weak infrastructures, which will be challenged to identify cases early and implement infection control procedures to limit continued transmission of the virus. - Mod.MPP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2469369,131.]
